content: The wide selection of sounds and the ability to create customized sound mixes are standout features of this app. But be aware that to cast audio from this app to a Chromecast Audio or any device other than a Chromecast video streamer, you will need to cast/mirror your entire phone's audio to that device. To do this, open the Google Home app, then go to Account (bottom right icon of a person in a circle) > Mirror Device > Cast Screen/Audio > select your device from the list. You should hear a sound and see a casting icon in your notifications. Then open the White Noise app and play your mix. If you are unable to connect at first, restarting your wifi network can help. All in all, this is a good app, but it would better if the ability to cast to CC Audio and CC-enabled speakers was baked directly into the app.
replyContent: Thanks for the review and feedback! Currently, to cast to audio only devices you‚Äôll need to download and use the Google Home app.  You can then add a Chromecast button to your notification drawer to mirror your audio to any Chromecast audio device including Google Home.  We apologize for any inconvenience this work-around causes.

I used White Noise Free on the first smartphone I had, and have since upgraded to the paid version on all phones since. On the whole, I like this app best of any white noise apps on the market. I like the ease of use, dark display, the ability to customize the sound by pitch, volume, and virtual orientation, as well as the ability to set alarms and duration. There are two downsides which stand out to me: 1) the setting for the full screen clock at night should use softer colors for the clock font (magenta or cyan on black isn't great for sleepy eyes). 2) I can tell when the soundbytes loop, and I'm immediately taken out of the peacefulness of the White Noise. It's totally a personal thing, totally and completely.  But I can only listen to my favorite soundbytes "Rain on Car Roof" and "Boat on the Water"(?) for so long, else they get repetitive. Longer soundbytes in the future would be a great improvement on an otherwise wonderful app.

Finally, an app that lets me set the pitch and frequency of the ocean waves! Love it. I also appreciate the opportunity to purchase the app instead of being teased with a free app that nickle and dimes me.

If you can't find the auto-haptic setting it may have gotten removed. There is a work around with a widget available on the google play store called "Auto Haptic Widget" that will disable the haptic feedbac

replyContent:
You may adjust the sleep clock by: Swiping left/right on the sleep clock will cycle through all the different colors. Dragging up/down on the screen will adjust brightness of the clock itself. Single tap of the screen dismisses the clock.

You may also go into settings and turn off the allow screen lock setting.

The latest update for this app asks for permission to write to and modify your SD card. Out the critical potentially dangerous permissions you should be cautious of allowing apps access to, this ranks high. There are of course a huge amount of legitimate reasons for granting this permission, such as an app that allows you to move it to the SD card needs this permission, or any app that allows you to save data to your SD card. As far as I know, you've never been able to do either with White Noise. Could that have changed? Certainly. But without the being considerate to security minded customers, and posting an explanation of why this permission is all of sudden being added with the update, well I'll never know what they are requesting this for. And with how many ways there are for apps to cause problems and vulgate privacy, well I'm not updating until they explain the need for the new permission. I would advise others against it as well.
